<P>In &s;uch employments he con&s;umed the greate&s;t part of his time; but, at la&s;t, finding the duties of his &s;tation daily encrea&s;ing, and his own &s;trength prop<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">rtionally upon the decline, he re&s;olved upon adopting a &s;ucce&s;&s;or. Marcus Antoninus, afterwards &s;urnamed the Pious, was the per&s;on he pitched up|on; but previou&s;ly obliged him to adopt two others, namely, Marcus Aurelius, and Lucius Verus, all of whom afterwards &s;ucceeded in the empire.</P>
